<br>
For those who think it's clear-cut one way or the other, let me ask you a question.  A girlfriend and boyfriend play on side-by-side computers.  Until the girlfriend gets home from work, sometimes the boyfriend plays her toon hydra.  (She's a cleric, so she's one of those group-critical roles.)  He's playing her toon hydra one day in a group, and something drops.  Does it really make a difference whether it dropped five minutes before or five minutes after she got home?  What if she got home before the item dropped, but forgot to announce that to the group?  And what if the boyfriend says in group, she just got home, but she hasn't said anything in group or tells yet, and soon afterwards something drops (so you can't really be sure who is running the toon at the moment of the drop)?  I'm not sure what's fair in any of those circumstances, arguments can be made both ways and I don't think any of them are unreasonable.  That's why talking about how loot will be split beforehand is the best idea.  <br>
<br>
Mostly, I see quite a spirit of generosity in pick-up groups.  Just yesterday, I was in PoV, and we were rolling on metallic liquid drops.  Two people had won rolls before I arrived, so they declined to roll on the next drop.  I tried to tell them that they should roll .. rolls they won before I arrived really shouldn't count .. but they insisted that they wouldn't roll.  And so it went, until everyone got a liquid (I was the last one).  If the others were being greedy, they would have rolled on every drop.  In fact, I really think they should have rolled against me when the sixth one dropped.  But they didn't, they just handed it to me, and that was that.  Nice people.  <br>
<br>
The parchment issue annoys me, though.  I've had plenty of casters suggest that only casters should roll on parchments, but then they want to roll on the droppable melee loot.  How is that fair?  The parchment may be no drop, but when turned in it becomes a droppable spell, which to my mind is no different than a droppable weapon.  If only casters get to roll on parchments, then only melees should be allowed to roll when a windblade drops.  Apparently, I am in the minority on this one, but it just doesn't seem right to me.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xamm>Xamm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(7/23/03 11:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3415.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Two Rolls or One Roll?</span><hr size=1> I agree with you about the windblades and parches, only the classes that need them should roll.  Most of my groups use this logic because I usually group with friends.  I've also grouped with tanks who won't be using the windblade as their primary so they just call it an open roll.  These are all things that should be discussed up front.  If everyone in EQ played with some common sense, it wouldnt be a big deal.  However everyone has grouped with that one loot whore who will insist on rolling for anything that is droppable.  These are the people that make me love soloing!   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vainne>Vainne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Night-blind Bard</span><br>  Posts: